review_blob: From bottle to glass.  Burnt sugar aroma, sort of like what you get off a creme brulee.  Very malty and sweet smelling.  Appearance is amber with a tan head.  Id call this one a sweet one relative to the German wheat and lager that I usually do.  Very thin and smooth as hell. Overall, OK.

This should be interesting.  When I think of English beer, I think of the famous stouts, ales, and IPAs.  I dont normally associate lagers with England.  Here goes: Pale golden color with high density white head.  Has that yeasty coconut smell that American lagers have and this one is pronounced even before the head fades away.  Taste is mild sweetness, but to put it in perspective; a high-quality version of an American lager. It has that yeasty-coconut smell with creamed corn characteristics. I dont like it.   For a good lager, you have to go to Bavaria or the Czech Republic. Ill leave the ales and stouts to the Brits, they do it well.
beer_name: Samuel Smiths Pure Brewed Organic Lager

review_blob: Very earthy aroma, typical Euro-lager, but stronger.  Hops, grains, leaves.  Very fresh and damp(but  not moldy).  Darker than the typical lager, and a nice foamy head that fades away quickly, letting out the aroma.  Taste is malty and has a slight bitter finish.  Overall, not bad. I thought the high booze would spoil it but it is a great brew.

From the big bottle to tulip.  I really wasnt expecting much, I just picked it up on a whim.  It surpristed the hell out of me.  Cloudy golden color with nice foam head.  Smells soooo good.  Citrus zest, mostly lemon, lime, and some orange.  Some fresh earthy notes too.  Taste is more like a mellow citrus beverage than a beer, but I really like it, and it is so smooth.  I had it alone, but they makers are correct, it begs to be paired with all sorts of clever foods.  I will totally pick a few more of these up and experiment with food pairings.  It has all the qualities of a Belgian Tripel without the spruce taste needle-like carbonation.

On tap at Grunauer.  Pale golden with nice white foam.  Earthy and herbal aroma, grains and hops.  Crisp grainy taste slight malty sweetness at first but finishing with some bitterness.  Perfectly balanced Euro-lager.  Great beer, and it was great to finally get some German brew from the tap.
Lemonade soda flavor.  Good for brunch, but you could probably make it yourself quite easily by mixing beer and lemon soda.
From bottle to glass.  Yeasty coconut flake aroma.  Mild sweet taste with mild bitter finish.  Other than that, it looks and feels like your typical pils. Completely average in my opinion.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: From half-liter bottle to glass.  Brown-amber cloudy tone with foamy head.  Strong banana aroma with spices and a yeasty note.  Medium sweet taste with slight bitterness in the end and a bit of a booze sting(or a sting from something). Bubbly carbonation (burp).  Overall, pretty good.

From bottle to glass. Malty sweet aroma with, rich malts, sweet bread, sugary icing, and faint creamed corn.  Golden amber cloudy color, a few shades darker than the typical lager.  Pretty darn sweet for a lager.  I think it is even sweeter that Hacker-Pschorr Oktoberfest beer.  Overall good, but it is a little sweeter than what I typically look for in a lager.

From bottle to glass.  Hay, corn aroma with some yeasty coconut aroma.  Slight sweet taste and mild bitterness in the end.  Kind of a foul meat aftertaste though.  Overall not bad, but not really all that good.  Its also quite overpriced.

From the can to glass.  Looks black on the table, ruby against the light.  Tan medium density head.  Head sticks around for a long time.  Dampens the aroma, but puts a nice icing on a gulp.  Aroma is strong chocolate, some oat-like grains, and damp earthiness. Medium sweetness with some alternating sour/bitter tastes.  Really good.

Corn, grass, and hay aroma.  Its really trying to put out that Euro-lager scent, but in the end it comes up short.  Wish I had some Chinese food to go with it.  Slight malt taste, mild sweetness and a mild bitter end.  Not bad

Bottle to tulip.  Black on the table, ruby against a light.  Dense head that fades away quickly allowing that beautiful aroma to escape.  Bread, spice, ginger, licorice.  Mild roast and with a small touch of sweetness.  Near-room temperature worked fine.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: I was directed here under an alias name. The label on what I am drinking right now is Hopfen-Weisse Hefe-Weizen Ale at 8.2% alc./vol.  From the bottle to the glass, it is cloudy tan and dark with a very low density head(large bubbles).  Smells like an American-style IPA and the head hasnt even faded away. Big whiff of hops and their array of pine and spruce zest.  Very floral as well.  Taste is a blend of American-style IPA craft-brew and traditional German Weizenbock.  Overall not bad, but just plain strange.

From the bottle to the glass.  Cloudy golden color with low-medium density head(large bubbles).  I let the head fade away to get the blunt force of the aroma.  Banana, spice, and a little bit of herb.  Medium sweetness with just a little sting from the booze.  Overall, delicious

From bottle to glass.  Strong yeasty funk aroma.  This is usually complemented by a faint coconut note.  Cloudy golden color with low-density head.  More aroma comes out after it fades away. Banana notes finally come out in the flavor, but that damn funky yeast smell kills it.  Overall my least favorite hefe so far.

From bottle to glass.  Earthy, herbal, damp, fresh aroma and a little yeasty.  Maybe a sparkle of fruit.  Cloudy color for sure, medium-high density white foam head.  Slight malt taste with dominant bitter ending. Unique.

From bottle to glass.  Smells like a Euro-lager but doesnt taste like one.  Aroma is light herbs, grass, earthy, flower leaves (not petals). Sort of a cutting chemical note in there as well.  Taste is mild malts and sweetness with a meaty and semi metallic aftertaste.  Overall not bad, but a definite contrast from the lagers of central Europe.  It seems more North-American than most lager from across the pond. Si visito a espaa la tomar, pero prefiero lager de alemania.
Just like grapefruit soda.  Carbonation like soda, taste like soda but with good not-to-sweet or syrup-like flavor.  Excellent for weekend brunch.
From bottle to glass.  Pumpkin seed and fall vegetable aroma with some coconut and pine zest.  Tastes like carbonated low alcohol whiskey. Blah.

From bottle to glass.  Cloudy brown, thick and white head that fades quickly, but what the hell. Candy sweetness aroma along with sweet bread dough, but it there is some nasty potent chemical lingering around. Tastes like it came from a chemical plant and not a brewery.  Nasty alcohol taste that destroys all the be flavor.
From bottle to glass.  Grassy aroma with some coconut peel. Mild sweet taste.  Overall, a great American lager.  I still prefer Euro-lagers, but this one is pretty darn good.

Dark amber cloudy color. Thick, creamy, white head.  Sweet bread dough and brown sugar aroma. When the head fades away a spicy note comes out.  Some candied fruit with the typical banana aroma developing quite late. When it does it is in more candied form than out of the peel.  Taste is very pine needle-like.  Not what I was expecting.  Prickly carbonation.  The taste is very close to the typical Belgian tripel style, although not as sprucy. Overall, not bad but this is not my favorite style of Weissbier.

Banana and spice aroma. Maybe just a tad bit of cherries and candy floating around, but very faint.  Fruity and sweet taste but in perfect proportion.
 Cloudy golden color with low-density head.  When it fades away that beautiful aroma really comes out.  Nobody makes wheat beer like the Germans, the best style by far.

Pronounced chocolate aroma along with the typical toasted oats cereal and earthy dampness of a dunkel. Some caramel and malt too.  Mild bitter taste and sweetness.  Reminds me of a bread-cake food item with some chocolate here and there.

Aroma is sweet bread, toasty like cereal.  When the head fades away it puts off more sweetness and caramel notes.  Dark brown but transparent color with tan creamy head.  Good flavor of grains, oats, and cereal with lager-like dampness.  Mild sweetness.  Finish is not so pleasant, and leaves a sort of spent beer taste in your mouth.

Toasty oat aroma with some bread, barley and caramel.  When the head fades away it really comes out.  Dark brown transparent color with creamy white head.  Very damp and earthy flavor. I really cant compare it to anything.  Not very sweet, not very bitter, but the flavor tastes a lot like it smells.

Grainy, cereal aroma.  After the head fades away you get some sweet and malty notes, maybe even some spruce.  Balanced cereal beverage with good flavor.  Not a bad brew at all and much better than I expected.

Im going to be honest.  I bought a bottle of this stuff because it featured a large moose-head on the label.  Some hay, grain, cereal and a touch of coconut aroma.  Its like a mixture of American-style lagers and Euro-lagers.  After the head fades away its just a tad too yeasty if that is what I smell.  Not a  bad taste, corn and mild sweetness, well-balanced by the hops.  A very neutral lager.  Only drawback is that yeasty, funk, coconut smell after the foam goes.
Cereal, malty bread, grainy.  Not bad but not good.  Very pronounced hoppy zest aroma.

Fresh aroma, corn, and hay. Maybe some sweetness that pokes around too.  Looks like any other pale lager/pils.  Malty thick taste for a lager.  Sweetness is pronounced where many other Euro-lagers exhibit bitter characteristics.  Carbonation is pretty high.  I would call this the only drawback.

Fresh, cool aroma.  Bread, hay, and some yeast funk.  Not a great one.  Taste just like it smells.  High carbonation.  Overall, this one isnt that great.  The first time I have been let down by a Munchen lager.
From the bottle.  Nice aroma.  Some hops, hay. Damp, cool, and fresh.  Bready taste with some hop zest and a bitter finish. I like it. Slightly better than average Euro-lager.

Has an aroma like furniture polish on top of cheap brewing cereal, very chemical-like.  Unpleasant taste too. This chemical taste spoils the beer.  Sort of sour.  I thought it had gone bad until I saw the expiration date claiming that this one still had several months to go.  This beer is downright terrible.

Syrup and  molasses on the smell, but not overly sweet. Maybe a few cocoa notes, but more like the type used for baking.  Very dark color.  I cant even get anything against a backlight.  Tan head, lasts quite a while for an imperial stout.  Roasty taste with some warming boozyness.  Just what you need on a 34 degree fall evening.  Great beer overall.  Great flavor, very drinkable, and a perfect cold-weather brew.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: Rated relative to real, non-alcoholic apple cider.  All the characteristics of apple cider with some fizz. This one is pretty good, but the 6% alcohol kills the cider flavor and makes it TOO thin.  Ive never made cider, but I think that ~3% would be friendly to the apples and retain the thickness, but still giving a fizzy, carbonated drink.
beer_name: J.K.s Scrumpy Orchard Gate Gold Hard Cider

review_blob: From the bottle to tulip.  Sweet, sugary, and  tart aroma. Maybe some sweet bread dough but not a very yeasty one.  Dark ruby-brown, almost black color with tan head.  Candy-like taste with booze.   Initially sweet then the booze kicks in.  Palate?  Overall, an OK cold-weather brew but sweetness and booze flavor is hard to balance.   This one in particular has gift appeal.

From the 1L can into the provided 1L glass.  This is the only way to get it where I live.  Can says ale, but it reminds me of a lager, a cheap one.  Certainly the stuff you put down by the liter.  Hoppy, earthy aroma, but not typical of most Bavarian brews.  Taste is bready, cereal, and a little honey sweetness.  Big carbonation and very thin.  Overall, not the best of Paulaner,  but I know it is designed to be consumed in bulk quantity.

From can to glass. Product of the UK?? wtf?? These nitro-brews will always have a two-dimensional flavor and aroma. Initial aroma is oats and light hops.  Damp, fresh, and Earthy. Clean.  Taste is very much the same with sweetness, and an instant rush of bitterness stomping it out.  Halfway through the beer, when you tilt the glass back, the foam floats to the back and you get nothing but the liquid.   This presents a more roasty and sour-milky aroma.  The taste goes to straight bitter and trades the sweetness for sourness.  The damp, earthy, and cool feel is still present.
Overall, a great alternative to Guinness due to equivalent flavor and lower price. (At least in the US)

From can to glass. Looks just like a Guinness, but favors dark brown over ruby brown.  In a casual situation youd have to be good to tell them apart. After the head settles you get some cocoa, roastiness, dark chocolate aroma.  Taste is two-dimensional.  With the head present you get dessert.  Cocoa, sweetness, and some bitter punches here and there during the finish.  With the glass half-full(or half empty) the foam floats to the back of the glass and you get the liquid in its infinite form with more sourness and milkyness.  Cool, damp, and Earthy. -But not moldy.  A little tingly and somewhat thick.  Overall, Id call this an upgraded Guinness. The chocolate flavor is a little dim for the name, but at least it is not fake or overwhelming.
From the jug.  Honey-like sweet taste with a decent bitter component to balance out.  Dark brown color.  Seems to go from sweet to bitter in a gulp.  Not bad, but not great either.
Dark, ruby color with tan head.  Taste is sweet, malty, sugary, molasses, dried fruit, cherries,  and bready.  A little on the sugary and sweet side for my taste.  Overall not bad.

From the can with a widget.  Sparkling, 5% ABV version of Johnnie Walker red.  There is some ale characteristics, but it screams of Johnnie red.  Notable finish.  Had one for lunch and I could still taste it after dinner.  Ugh.

OMG I love this beer, from the can de el centro de los estados unidos.  Typical Euro-lager aroma; herbal, meaty, zesty, fresh like standing water without the mold, golden colour with nice head.  Has a grainy taste, very well balanced. The light flavour of malt is present along with the hops.  Overall this is going to be one of my favorites.  Has everything I love about Euro-lagers and an aluminum container I can take to the pool. A bargain on price.

Herbal toasty aroma, maybe a little bit piney and zesty.  Looks like apple juice with nice head of small-bubbles.  Taste is just plain bitter and doesnt let any other flavors through even if you let it warm up a little.  Overall a very one-dimensional IPA.  The bitterness should complement the other characteristics of beer, not smother them.

From the swingtop bottle to a pils glass. Aroma is a little earthy, metallic, hoppy, and grainy.  Clear golden lager color.  
Taste is slightly bitter with the usual lager beer characteristics.  I would throw this one in the slightly bitter pale lager category.  Feels a little tingly and thin.  Overall a little on the bitter side but not bad.  Neat bottle.

From bottle to tulip, an of course the brew wasnt served at fridge temperature.  Aroma is very light of the following: tart, tangy, oats and candy sweetness.  Looks dark, but against a light it is translucent ruby with no particulate.  Taste is just barely deflects the neutral category with a light tangy sweetness.  Not much in the way of flavor.  Feels thin, but fizzy.  Overall, nothing special.  Average ratings across the board for this one.

From bottle to glass.  Zesty, pine, and citrus for dominant scent. Some bread and cereal lingers on too, mostly after the head fades away.  Has a straw colored appearance like most pilsners.  Taste is mostly bitter. Hoppy like an IPA.  An interesting take on Pilsner, but I dont like the bitterness.  I need to stick with Euro-pilsners. Re-rate notes: After several more, this is just too much like an IPA, and a lousy one at that.  Sam Adams makes a delicious whitewater IPA so I know they can do it well, but this pils is just terrible.

From bottle to chalice.  Yeasty, hoppy aroma.  Doughy, grassy, sprucy, cheesy,  hide, boozy, zesty.  More aroma comes out after the head fades away. Hazy copper-orange color. Taste is bitter, some sweet and sour towards the end, but not much.  Overall, not really what Im into.  It is quality, but not my style.

From bottle to tall glass.  Has the same aroma as Paulaner original Munich lager but much more faint.  Earthy, stone, damp, and fresh.  Looks like any other pale lager.  Taste is slightly on the sweet side with a cancelling bitterness.  Very soft and somewhat oily, sticky feel.  Goes down like water.  Very easy drinking.  Overall, I like it.  Its good to have beer available that wont put you on the floor.
